Do you have a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair a broken road system, many begin to see the solution in a small black box neatly arranged on your car’s dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile driven by a motorist and transmit this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by the planning authorities of Washington and the state.
Usually, the boring highway planning arena has unexpectedly spawned intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and possibly even where you drive them—and then use that information in the compilation of tax bills.
The tea-drinking movement in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions about privacy.
And while Congress cannot yet agree on whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They’re thinking about how you can switch over the next decade to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already tested these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“That’s not the question we might have a choice about,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to start tracking the state’s mileage traveled by each California motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in how we pay these taxes.
The technology already exists for this.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government Fund for the construction of highways, funded by taxes that Americans pay on gasoline stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars drive more than a mile per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not been raised for 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise taxes by even one cent at high gasoline prices.
“It’s simply impossible to keep the gasoline tax,” said Lee Mannich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the error payment system.
“It will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
Boredom calls this a misleading user charge.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, as with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California’s planning authorities are monitoring this system as they develop strategies to achieve the targets set by the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, House Speaker Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Adherents of the free market in the “Reason” fund are also delighted that they will make drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that will go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. transport ministers who in 2011 called on Congress to move toward mispayment.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would involve about 10,000 cars.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of fears of rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles in everyday life to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, are on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are attracted to participate in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track every step of their way.
“The concern about the big brother and things like that is a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
When the tests were in full swing, the U.S. Civil Liberties Union office in Nevada warned on its website: “It will be quite easy to turn these devices into full-scale tracking devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of the few states that are conducting difficult searches for cheap technology that would allow state authorities to take into account the mileage traveled by car, but without information about location and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more relaxed.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not involved in assisting in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of car insurance, in which drivers pay on a mileage basis.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is downloaded periodically using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been several major errors in some of these state pilot programs.
There are far less expensive and less compulsive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can completely abandon the device, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
In other places, they hope to sell the idea to a cautious public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transportation officials are keen to develop a taxation device that will also accept parking meter payments, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect real-time speed data pools from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists will be attracted to the benefits that they will be offered,” – says the document of urban design.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering whether all talk of mispayment is simply a huge distraction.
In the San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Construction Trust Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid drivers and others whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgical intervention when all you have to do is take aspirin,” said Randy Rentshler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a host of other things.
