Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of rising risks to Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather, the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is completely driven by consumption, which almost does not slow the turnover," said Goldman Sachs chief economist for Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation at 6%, it will be able to meet future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is declining, so they are likely to optimise personnel costs.
Today, we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages increase by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - Mr Grafe explained.
The companies are facing a decline in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to redundancies and rising unemployment.
The Russian business cannot raise salaries, commented the chief economist of Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyuschyn.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees out or retain current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is undergoing a very rapid growth in borrowing.
According to Mr. Graf, because of the extremely high interest rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the economy of the country.
“We haven’t seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, money doesn’t spread across the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects a rise in overdue unsecured loans.
They are mostly taken by poor people, who have nothing to provide.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often,” said Graphe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of default on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, Director of the Banking Institute of the HSE, already sees signs of an impending banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, having no access to cheap resources, such as state banks, were forced to raise public funds at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to lower the loan rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up dumping, Russia is in danger of a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks the economist considers a forerunner of a massive collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was originally not designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, - due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing tariffs on natural monopolies (and, as a result, reducing inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the guide), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushyn of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is the continued fall in oil prices,” he says.
According to him, Russia’s economy will begin to shrink at a price of oil below $90/barr.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet in a position to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has fallen, and banks have started raising rates.
This could mean that they didn’t believe the central bank, which announced the transition to targeting inflation,” said Clemens Graphe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,” said Clemens Graphe.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not to lend the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate changes immediately, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later the Central Bank will understand that this strategy is not working,” Graphe said, reminding that the state plans to release the ruble into “free flow” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it earlier, or raise the central bank’s key rate (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the rate of the ruble is now artificially exceeded by 10%.
There is only one way to lose weight, says the expert.
But if the Central Bank plunges in the financiers at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy of weakening the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much stronger.
