Snowden ready to “cooperate” with Germany on U.S. intelligence issue
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was ready to go to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, could not answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr Snowden, which the deputy presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: "Although the result of my efforts was clearly positive, my government continues to treat disagreement as treason and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that do not give anything."
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the US government to abandon criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make this possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany became tense after allegations that the NSA was listening to Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a deputy who heads a parliamentary group that oversees intelligence, said if there is an opportunity to listen to Mr Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him or completely destroying relations with the United States,” it should be used.
Mr. Str<0xC3><0xB8>bele, a member of parliament from the Green Party of Germany, posted his photo with Mr. Snowden on Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Str<0xC3><0xB8>bele said that, according to the lawyer of the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not have returned to Russia if he had left.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need assurances that he would be “safe there,” the deputy said.
Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and constant” campaign of persecution that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was inspired by the global response to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials—including in the United States—have found the disclosure of an uncontrolled system of all-out surveillance to be beneficial to society.
The letter proposes to cooperate with the German authorities "when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation will be solved".
Frontier Airlines will charge a fee for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although their announcement on Wednesday said passengers will be able to keep the entire bank.
The new fee for hand luggage extends to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would only pay when they landed.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said a $100 fee should make passengers pay in advance.
“We don’t want to pay for it,” she said.
The airlines began charging for the first and second bags to be handed in in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges are loading as much as they can into the hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why these compartments often lack space.
Fees are one way to make passengers carry less on board.
O'Malley said this new tax wasn't really about making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that finding a place in the top luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in a queue at the start of the Frontier flight may be able to carry a bag for free, while the next passenger in a queue may pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the change in procedures on the website and at the Frontier check-in stands was meant to ensure passengers would know about the collection before they get to the boarding gate.
The new Frontier fee for hand luggage will not start to be charged until the summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other fees, but airlines love them.
They claim that handling baggage costs money, and passengers who need this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after several years of losses.
However, most of them did not touch the fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first manual set fee three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
According to his December 2011 report, the cost of hand luggage brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines top manager, recently flew a Spirit flight, and he was interested in what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers encountered an unusual Spirit baggage charge.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my airline career,” he said.
I was expecting to see the teeth crunch and the appearance of a fight at the exit to the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire can and that the coffee will be provided free of charge.
It will continue to provide water for free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but gave up seven months after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
The Frontier initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket vendors such as Orbitz, from $10 to $25 for every ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting the online travel agency.
Frontier, however, went beyond everyone in this area.
In September, she began giving twice as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, it cut the premium mileage to 25 percent of the travel mileage.
For example, a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would earn 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming lossy.
Revenue fell by 9 percent, and flight options fell by nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix the finances of Frontier as part of the airline's sale.
NSA blames “internal error” not hackers in stopping the site
The National Security Agency said Friday night that shutting down their site for several hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as claimed on the network.
“NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during the scheduled update,” the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The statement that the interruption was caused by a distributed denial-of-service attack [DDoS] is incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems reported that the NSA’s website hadn’t worked for at least six hours, and the site was still inaccessible to some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency's internal secret network was "not hacked".
No classified information is at risk, the spokesman said.
At least one online group of hacker activists said it was responsible for decommissioning the NSA’s website via a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to clutch the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site goes out of business.
The tactics of hackers are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
Previously, the super-secret NSA, once nicknamed "No Such Agency", was in recent months in the center of public attention and fierce criticism after a series of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and within the country - all this is a reaction to the secret files of the NSA.
The growing controversy around the agency has prompted speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
Bombardier’s profit declines with drop in deliveries and aircraft orders
Bombardier, a Canadian aircraft and trains manufacturer, reported a 15 percent reduction in net profit on Thursday due to declining orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and contract problems in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not released any flight test data for its latest CSeries aircraft and has not provided new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be implemented.
After the first flight of an experimental sample of the aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the testing stage is on schedule.
The results did not justify the forecasts and led to a fall in stocks by more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerxen, a National Bank Financial analyst, on Thursday lowered his valuation from “over-medium” to “medium” because of the belief that stock growth is limited in the coming quarter or two.
“Although the decrease in the number of aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed by the profit indicators of the transport department,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first experimental sample of the aircraft was presented in March and made its first flight in September after several months of delay.
However, the firm orders for CSeries are not yet too many – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for flight test results to test the company’s claims about fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
There are currently 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Bodouan was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft would be put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, the leaders also assured analysts and media that the program is moving forward as planned.
