All manufacturers plan the tests differently.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is expected to fly in the coming weeks and all the rest will soon follow it, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical about the statement that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the timeline for commissioning and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing – although apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule – supports our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same – 9 cents.
Gross income declined slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected a profit of 10 cents per share and gross income of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
