“In the aerospace field, the results matched our goals, but the small number of orders received and general market conditions became an unpleasant factor,” Boduan said.
Gross revenue in the aerospace sector fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector grew by almost 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure from December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were adversely affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pichett will join the board of directors, fell by 8.5 percent to $4.83 in auctions on mid-Thursday.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and closest competitor to Bombardier, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
Sony Expects Lower Annual Profits
The Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony Corporation, having completed the past quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, has cut its profit forecast for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s July-September 2013 results were more disappointing than expected due to a drop in demand for Japanese-made TVs, video cameras and personal computers.
Sony's TV business, which brought the company its first operating profit in three years of 5.2 billion yen, fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operating loss in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is experiencing difficult times, especially due to the decline in demand for televisions.
And while competitors are striving to find a way out of a difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
