The speech gene has been shown to stimulate the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the Foxp2 speech gene performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 through the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
The researchers found that family members had a disruption of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function was not known.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulant for the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with speech formation.
This is accomplished by another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 deriving its activity.
That SRPX2 actually affects vocalization, the scientists confirmed in the experiment on mice.
When the gene activity of animals was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated from the mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the emitted sounds was also restored.
Previously, the mice also showed a link to the vocalization of Foxp2.
Animals that received a human copy of the gene were fed more actively and at a lower frequency than regular mice.
So far, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 controlled by it is related to purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
