Obama's Pre-election Staff Considered Biden's Exclusion in Favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama’s closest advisers were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton in the 2012 election list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation in all of Mark Galperin’s and John Heilemann’s 2012 campaign Double Bets: The Game Has Changed 2012.
The Times received a copy of the book in preparation and said Thursday evening that the president’s closest aides had conducted “large-scale research into focus groups and public opinion polls at the end of 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exclusion could help raise the waning hopes for re-election.
According to The Times political commentator Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempts of senior officials of the Pre-election Staff and the White House, namely former White House administration chief Bill Daley, to assess what effect the appointment of the former Vice-Secretary of State will have on the vote.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded in the Chicago election headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former President Obama’s Chief of Staff Jim Messina, and former White House senior advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book Double Bets claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden, despite their "close personal relationship", but eventually abandoned that step when their data showed that adding Clinton to the ballot box would not "significantly improve Obama's chances".
In an interview with Martin Daley, he confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden Clinton.
“I actively advocated a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the newspaper.
You must remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, ‘Oh my God, what are we going to do?’
Although Daley described the study as a “necessary verification,” Martin told CNN spokesman Anderson Cooper that the election staff had invested enough in exploring whether the move would bring dividends to the vote.
“Election staffs don’t spend such amounts of money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously,” Martin said in the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was considering a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then boss knew about the possible crossover.
Although Daley said he didn’t think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former head of the administration admitted that “maybe” Obama knew.
Martin added that Double Bets does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political survey have reached Obama’s table.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believed that Obama was unaware of the study of the possibility of excluding Biden from the electoral roll.
“Maybe,” Martin said.
