And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the narration of an ancient fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey the orders of Europe?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposing the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the “Alternative for Germany” Eurosceptic party – founded only this year – emerged from nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, essentially displacing the “Free Democrats” (the analogue of our “Liberal Democrats”) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the chains imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the “Europe” project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments working with excessive budget deficits – this was true only for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates profitable to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself in a precarious position in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only way to save is to cut wages and public spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of budget and currency lies a deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacities.
As a result of the “green” energy package introduced by Brussels, a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the US.
These are paralyzingly unfavourable price conditions, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
No freezing of wages in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, the rebellion ripens, especially in France, once the most ferocious supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and it has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s ruined economy in dire straits.
The result is the right-wing anti-EU Marine Le Pen National Front party has just won crucial additional elections, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to British Labourers that one cannot assume that the split between the right will automatically turn in favor of the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties get support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to take the dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: the soon-to-be growing sentiments against the EU and against the single currency in Europe are merging to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will once again become something of a flimsy “Europe of (sovereign) nations” liked by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several dependent economies can keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will rebuild their own currencies.
I guess the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that the UK will go unnoticed in the cold Atlantic.
In what way does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (in fact) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed within the framework of a more free European agreement, provided that we preserve our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in the non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and maintaining our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is – strangely enough – the most successful political movement in Europe, directed against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to the cuts in expenditures proposed (and implemented) by the Labour Party and the Chancellor of the Treasury.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to now vote for independence only to take the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early sexual maturation: aging earlier
African-American and Latino girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that sexual maturation is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency towards early sexual maturity is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etterij is a journalist specializing in child health and family matters.
Should a mother be frightened if her daughter starts to form mammary glands and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years of age?
At the annual American Academy of Pediatrics conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents — it usually doesn’t mean a rapid onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there was only a slight shift in menarche age (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and has fallen from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it goes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of the book “Early sexual maturation in girls: how to deal with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate verification of how sexual maturation will progress.
There is a debate about what constitutes an actual onset of sexual maturity, but is considered “premature” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop – this is something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of bones, which can eventually lead to slow growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child’s age, developmental level, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with medications, but admits that “suppression of sexual maturation can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruation at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we were talking about menstruation, she wasn’t emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many popular theories about the causes of early sexual maturation.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, as in girls, sexual maturation occurs earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the prerequisite that has the greatest weight is an obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls between the ages of 6 and 9, which linked the amount of fat in the body to the period of puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations.
All over the world, early sexual maturation appears to be influenced by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency towards full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of crib age.
“We need to be careful about how we define the true onset of sexual maturity,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a paediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be shy about receiving instructions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier than usual, this process is a normal part of life.
