A new anti-nicotine vaccine may deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from lifelong nicotine dependence.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Medical College Wales Cornell in New York said the first results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the techniques available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from getting a nicotine attack.
In the tests, vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activity.
And mice that weren’t given the vaccine “relaxed,” and this is a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have been unsuccessful because they contain antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of a new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into factories of antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get that pleasure from the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of that habit,” he said.
