Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They should not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain gives "good".
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the plane is down for landing, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and steering, the FAU said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Boarders, welcomed these changes.
“After the new policy is implemented safely (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option,” Glading said.
We are frankly tired of feeling “school duty” when it comes to this issue.
But internet connection for surfing, sharing emails, texting or downloading data will still be banned at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there is still no "Words with Friends" - an intelligent internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a crazy case: the actor was taken off an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device at the time the plane was on.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be put in the trunk, as they can hurt someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also continue to be banned.
Regulatory powers on telephone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU.
The FAU may lift the ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosencker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transport safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know from the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAU to study the issue recommended last month that the government allow more use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been increased pressure on the FAU to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McKaskill, argue that there are no solid reasons for bans related to security.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure as the application of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radio receivers - high-tech gadgets of the time.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by the FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of the liners are adapted for wider use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book reading devices, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those seeking to mitigate restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company downloaded an entire airliner with their Kindle e-book readers and flew on it to check for problems, but never detected them.
The members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings as to whether the use of devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he believes interference from devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only individual reports from pilots confirming that the devices could cause interference to aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAU allow pilots to require passengers to turn off the devices during landings on the instruments in limited visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards passengers who are now using many technological devices.
“We are delighted that the FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Tourism Association.
