Scientists have shed light on how the movements of the dog's tail are related to her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs twist their tails to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs swing their tails predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family may notice these subtle differences in tailing and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at Trent University, says: “It is well known that people on the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like humans, the right part of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To find out more about how dogs respond to the diverse tailings of other dogs, researchers watched the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
Probably soon we will understand why their tails are sometimes pointed in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed dogs videos with dogs – either naturalistic versions or a silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that in the rest, a non-expressive dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of a waving-tailed dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was tilting predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog’s tilting tail), their heartbeat increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should worry about and what they shouldn’t.
He notes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs, and their tails are often twisted in one direction to be more friendly, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these findings can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their pet’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest scientist at the University of Bristol’s veterinary school, said this was not the first study to check whether left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another scientific paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the forking of its tail was directed to the left rather than the right, rather than becoming alarmed, the opposite behavior to the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be a useful study of how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is enough evidence from different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails are sometimes pointed in one direction and sometimes in the other.
