Travel through dirt, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking hundreds of patients
In this West African country, there are not so many doctors – only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of CNN's top 10 heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall unconscious again, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a 1981 car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused hematoma, which resembled itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
“You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would not be in their pockets.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare spending in the country is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“Because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwellet and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are loaded into vans, tied to the roofs of medical supplies and drive across the intersection to visit the villagers in need of help.
They don't always get lucky.
Many times they had to push cars through rivers and dirt.
But when they arrive, they are met as real heroes: it’s a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that only the locals can offer.
The free medical care in these villages is indeed an occasion for celebration, and Bwelle with his broad smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the brigade began to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on each trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a 60-kilometre radius of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get cribs, donated glasses, or free birth certificates—documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, municipality or in a house; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating and sanitary equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s an unstoppable pace, but the team’s determination usually helps support the village musicians.
“They’ve been knocking drums all night so we can stay awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the crew members go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of tremendous importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” he said.
In addition to these clinical admissions on weekends and work at the hospital, the surgeon Bwell also works overnight in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest of the funds are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a Bwell group volunteer.
He is either always in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O’Malley, who come from the US and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, this is an opportunity of practice that they would never get at home.
“We had the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arriving at Yaoundé, their food, transportation and training pay Bwell.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, nearly constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others live a happy life, fulfilling their father’s promise is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to lessen their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
