The agency "Rosbalt" deprived of the status of the media for the obscene fight
On October 31, the Moscow court decided to invalidate the license on the registration of the Rosbalt agency, - writes "Lenta".
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of media status - for systematic and gross violations of the law on media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact denying the publication the right to put forward counterarguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
ZAO "Rosbalt Information Agency" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has representations in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytics agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was included in the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the closeness of the publication to the force structures continued throughout the agency's existence.
Besides the fact that "Rosbalt" had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions it was said that the project was led by Natalia Chaplin - the wife of Victor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplin’s role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: she is most often called the “project manager”.
The director general of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, "Rosbalt" did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation, nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency ranked 25th in the ranking of visits to Russian media sites according to the LiveInternet version.
According to LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes on the helplessness of the Kremlin in its relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Joke", pogroms in the capital, Biryulevo.
Rosbalt’s conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the media law came into force, prohibiting journalists from engaging in obscene fighting.
The agency found a banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot polluted oil towers").
The other sides describe it differently.
Roskomnadzor accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the media law on the basis of the video footage found and appealed to the court with the requirement to withdraw a license from the agency.
Rosbalt stated that the agency's claims were wrong: first, the videos were not editorial materials, second, the mother words in them were disguised, and, third, immediately after warning the videos were removed from the site.
The agency’s representatives appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims to the World Court – and when the Moscow Court accepted Roskomnadzor’s lawsuit on October 22, 2013, the examination of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th the world judge made a decision not in favor of "Rosbalt": the editor-in-chief Nikolay Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offences and fined 20,000 rubles - 10 thousand for each roll.
Apparently, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Mosgorsud - if you give up the thought that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It is not possible to say that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (a statement on behalf of the head of the Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted on the initiative of the KPRF).
Vsevolod Bogdanov, head of the Union of Journalists of Russia, Pavel Gusev, chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists, and Mikhail Fedotov, head of the Presidential Council on Human Rights, declared the illegality of the closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even gave him some guarantees that the issue will not come before the withdrawal of the license.
The court over Rosbalt showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be in the media in Russia today is a big question.
