John Kerry says in his unprecedented confession that U.S. espionage “has gone inappropriately far”
John Kerry demonstrated a softening of the tactics of protecting U.S. surveillance programs, making an unprecedented admission that in some cases U.S. espionage “has gone inappropriately far.”
The secretary of state also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being “on autopilot” at the time of Edward Snowden’s outspoken revelations about NSA spying.
These leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic scandal with its allies.
Speaking on video at an open government conference in London, Mr. Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the President and I, as well as other members of the government, actually perceived some of the things that were happening on autopilot, because such an opportunity already existed – both during the Second World War, and in the very difficult years of the Cold War.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to acknowledge that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that no one’s rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it has gone inappropriately far.
And the president is determined to shed light on the issue and explain himself to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis to ensure that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted on good grounds and that his surveillance operations saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow people up and attack governments.
What if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and killing people because we were able to find out about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism activities with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important in the interests of U.S. national security that Europeans remain our supporters of our common counter-terrorism efforts,” Murphy, a Democrat serving in the first term and chairman of the Senate’s subcommittee on international relations on European affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
“And I am going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at these NSA programs.”
News that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected misunderstandings of metadata collected by NATO allies and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations cited Snowden-released documents suggesting that the NSA was monitoring German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended espionage activities against the Allies as necessary and said it was an ordinary matter on both sides.
Against this backdrop, Murphy said his office was organizing a visit from members of Congress expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other lawmakers will be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still in the development stage.
Although Murphy stated that the purpose of the trip was to promote better relations, he said that some degree of “hardness from the best motivations” would also be manifested.
He said that European leaders should be honest with their people in what spy programs they themselves have used for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also have to agree with the fact that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry should travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to address the problems of hostility towards the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
