Australian Woman Appeals Against Imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming that she had been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on June 15 by the Phuket provincial court of filing a false lawsuit after Thailand police reported that a local taxi driver had carried out the attack on the night of Sunday, June 10, while two other men were holding her.
However, video surveillance footage later revealed that she had returned safely to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before admitting to having fabricated the story.
Prior to her trial, she had been held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence in a general regime detention facility on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than a female adult prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Canberra Foreign Ministry for help for her daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about his daughter’s well-being and was waiting for her to return to Australia.
“Obviously, it was an alarming time, but we hope that she will return home safely as soon as possible,” Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the Krabi resort area in southern Thailand.
Thailand-based legal sources said Bamford is currently representing a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could result in the court increasing her sentence to up to two years and forcing her to serve an adult prison term.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michel Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, leading to an acquittal.
